06591nam a22007575i 9780774853750DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20071996xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748537507 a10.59962/97807748537502doi  a(DE-B1597)662208  a(OCoLC)1148083902  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHC120.E5bA24 1996eb 7aNAT0110002bisacsh04a333.7/097100aAchieving Sustainable Development /ced. by John B. Robinson, Ann Dale. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (317 p.) :b31 b&w illustrations, 18 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSustainability and the Environment00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tVisions -- tLife in 2030: The Sustainable Society Project -- tSustainability Strategies and Green Planning: Recent Canadian and International Experience -- tConnections -- tGrowing Wisely: Reconciling Competitiveness and Sustainability in a Shrinking World -- tAction -- tBiodiversity Conservation: A Decision-Making Context -- tIndustrial Ecology: Efficient and Excellent Production -- tMaking Sustainable Development Happen: Institutional Transformation -- tPutting Women and the Environment First: Poverty Alleviation and Sustainable Development -- tPromises, Promises: Canadian Campaign Rhetoric, Agenda 21, and the Status of Women -- tAboriginal Peoples: The Basis for Policy-Making toward Sustainable Development -- tAssessing Progress -- tA Systemic Approach to Assessing Progress toward Sustainability -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe recent United Nations Conference on the Environment and Development, popularly known as the Earth Summit, was a milestone event for sustainable development. In dealing with ecological and developmental issues concurrently, it brought the international environmental agenda to the fore. Canada was the first industrialized country to announce that it would be a signatory to the Biodiversity Convention, and by furthering future forestry and global warming conventions, it played an important leadership role. Achieving Sustainable Development explores how well Canada has met the Earth Summit's targets and attempts to find ways in which the public can become involved in such issues. Its authors stress the importance of integration of information from various fields and seek to stimulate the exchange of knowledge among the academic community, government, non-governmental organizations and industry. The contributors look far beyond merely identifying and analyzing selected issues and problems. To facilitate public discussion and to affect policy development, at least one initiative is proposed and detailed for each problem identified. Achieving Sustainable Development provides an overall introduction to critical subjects in sustainable development -- industrial growth, women, institutional arrangements, industrial practices, and aboriginal peoples. Most importantly, it argues for the immediate development of a research and policy agenda for Canada and suggests mechanisms for its implementation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aBerkes, Fikret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBers, Caroline Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCôté, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDale, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDale, Ann, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFast, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab